{
  "title": "2.8 CONSEQUENCES OF RESOURCE USE CONFLICT BETWEEN FARMERS AND PASTORALISTS",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "a14bab6b4e77f554",
      "text": "Resource use conflict has a number of implications for the society. It can lead to scarcity of food as farmers often abandon their farms for self preservation and therefore there is no cultivation of crops. Primate Samson Ojoawo, President-General of Grassroots Farmers Association (GFA) in Saki, emphasized this point in an interview conducted with him. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "33ccf5fe71fd5d2a",
      "text": "He was of the view that unless the issue of conflicts between farmers and herdsmen in Saki (and Oke-Ogun) was addressed, very urgently, there would be food shortage in Oyo State since Oke Ogun is regarded as the food basket of the State. According to him, farmers in Saki West Local Government Area (L.G.A) and Oke-Ogun were becoming frustrated by the destructive acts of herdsmen and have started to quit farming for other vocations."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0f4e5f1db02d4229",
      "text": "Secondly, because of the possible linkage between resource use conflict and conflicts in the West African sub region, a resource use conflict may escalate into a national or regional war. A case in point is the Tuareg region in   Mali and Niger Republic where the ongoing conflict is said to have resource-use undertone.  Also, the 1983 war between Nigeria and Chad started from the conflict between fishermen of the two countries (Shettima &Tar ).It has also been observed that the Darfur crisis in Sudan started as a resource conflict."
